ZARVA CORE ARCHITECTURE PROTOCOL (ZCAP)
Version 2 — Feature-Sliced Design Edition
This is the permanent constitution of the ZARVA codebase. This is NOT a suggestion guide — it is a strict structural mandate. Every new feature, bug fix, or AI task MUST pass through this protocol before a single line of code is written.
When given a development command, clearly differentiate what belongs to React Native (mobile app) and what belongs to the Node.js server. All secrets, sensitive logic, and core processing must remain inside the Node.js backend. The mobile app handles only UI, user input, and API communication.
Always structure responses by clearly separating:

📱 Mobile (React Native)
🖥 Server (Node.js)
🔐 Security considerations (if applicable)

The server must always be the source of truth.
Project locations:

/ — Node.js server project
/zarva-mobile — React Native project


🛑 SECTION 0: THE PRIME DIRECTIVES (Zero Tolerance Policy)
Directive 1 — Server-First Processing
Mandate: ALL business logic, mathematical calculations, pricing, job state management, matching algorithms, worker eligibility, and sensitive operations MUST live entirely on the Node.js backend.
Mobile Restriction: The React Native app is strictly a "dumb client". It handles ONLY UI rendering, user input capture, device APIs (location/notifications), and pushing data to the server.
The mobile app must NEVER:

Calculate a price or fee
Determine a job phase locally
Process payments directly
Control job state
Validate payments
Decide worker eligibility
Control retries or counters

Trust Zero Clients: Assume the mobile app is compromised. Validate, sanitize, and authorize every single request on the server.
Directive 2 — The Trifecta Synchronization Rule (MySQL → Firebase → FCM)
Mandate: MySQL is the permanent Source of Truth for all state. Firebase Realtime Database is a temporary mirror for instant UI reactivity. FCM is for waking up clients.
Execution Order — never deviate:

Write to MySQL (commit the transaction)
Write to Firebase (update the mirroring node)
Fire FCM notification (wake up the intended user)

Never allow Firebase and MySQL to diverge. Firebase is a read mirror only.
Directive 3 — Secrets and Tokens
Mandate: JWTs and sensitive credentials on mobile MUST be stored using expo-secure-store. Never use AsyncStorage for secrets.
Directive 4 — Mobile vs Server Boundary
When in doubt about where logic belongs, ask the user before proceeding. Always structure responses separating 📱 Mobile, 🖥 Server, and 🔐 Security.

🗺️ SECTION 1: NEW FEATURE INTAKE PROTOCOL
Before writing any code, run through this checklist in order:
Step 1 — Classify the Feature

UI only? → Mobile Protocol (Feature-Sliced Design, Section 2)
Logic/Data only? → Backend Protocol (Section 3)
Real-time reactivity? → Firebase Protocol (Trifecta Rule, Directive 2)
Money/Pricing? → Backend Service + Idempotency (Section 3)

Step 2 — Prevent Duplication
Search the API Contract Map, Store Fields, and existing UI Components. If an entity exists, extend it. Do not rebuild it.
Step 3 — Identify the Blast Radius
Which existing files, API contracts, store fields, and UI behaviors will this change impact? Document them before touching any code.
Step 4 — Trace the Data Flow
Map: User input → UI → Feature store → API call → Node.js service → MySQL → Firebase mirror → FCM notification.

📱 SECTION 2: MOBILE PLACEMENT MAP (React Native) — /zarva-mobile
The mobile project uses Feature-Sliced Design (FSD). Every piece of mobile code has exactly one correct home.
2.1 — The Four Layer Hierarchy
Lower layers must NEVER import from higher layers. Features must NEVER import from each other.
LayerFolderRule1 — Appsrc/app/App.js, RootNavigator, ThemeProvider, GlobalLoader, providers.jsx. Can import from any layer.2 — Featuressrc/features/One folder per domain. Each owns its screens, store, API, hooks, types, translations. May import from Shared and Infra only — never from each other.3 — Sharedsrc/shared/Reusable UI (ZButton, OTPInput), hooks, design system, i18n engine, shared types. No business logic. May import from Infra only.4 — Infrasrc/infra/Third-party integrations: apiClient, Firebase, AsyncStorage, FCM init, env config. No React components. No business logic.
2.2 — Feature Folder Structure (Standard Pattern)
Every feature follows this identical internal structure:
src/features/<name>/
  index.js              — Public exports only. Nothing else imports from inside.
  screens/              — React Native screens for this feature
  components/           — UI components used only by this feature
  store.js              — Zustand store for this feature
  api.js                — All API calls for this feature
  hooks/                — Feature-specific custom hooks
  types.js              — JSDoc / TypeScript types
  translations/         — Per-feature i18n files
    en.js  ml.js  hi.js  ta.js
